---
import ProjectLayout from '../../layouts/ProjectLayout.astro';
---

<ProjectLayout
  title="tomeaves.dev"
  description="This portfolio website, built from scratch using Astro, HTML and CSS. Designed to be easy to update with new projects and blog posts."
  tags={{
    action: [
      { label: 'Visit Site', url: 'https://tomeaves.dev' },
      { label: 'Source Code', url: 'https://github.com/tomeaves-dev/portfolio' },
    ],
    status: 'Released',
    tech: ['Astro', 'HTML', 'CSS', 'MDX', 'Node.js'],
  }}
>

  <h2>About the Project</h2>
  <p>
    You're looking at it. This site is built from scratch using <strong>Astro</strong> with plain
    HTML and CSS — no UI frameworks, no component libraries. The goal was a fast, easy to maintain
    portfolio that I could update with new projects and blog posts without fighting a CMS or a template.
  </p>
  <p>
    Blog posts are written in <strong>MDX</strong>, project pages are <strong>Astro</strong> components,
    and the whole thing deploys automatically to <strong>GitHub Pages</strong> on every push to main.
  </p>

  <Fragment slot="tech">
    <p>
      Built with <strong>Astro 6</strong>, chosen for its static-first approach and zero JavaScript
      by default. Styles are plain CSS using custom properties for theming. Blog posts use
      <strong>MDX</strong> for Markdown with the option to drop in Astro components where needed.
      Syntax highlighting is handled by Astro's built-in <strong>Shiki</strong> integration.
      Deployed to GitHub Pages via a GitHub Actions workflow.
    </p>
  </Fragment>

  <Fragment slot="learned">
    <p>
      Building a site from scratch rather than reaching for a template forced me to make deliberate
      decisions about every design choice. It also gave me a much better understanding of CSS layout,
      custom properties, and how static site generators work under the hood.
    </p>
  </Fragment>

</ProjectLayout>